# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no equivalent needed
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never thrown** by the runtime

The old pattern of "abort thread → catch `ThreadAbortException` → rollback" is completely gone. The modern replacement is **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        // Task.Run uses the thread pool — no manual Thread management
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cooperative cancellation requested — roll back and exit
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        // Signal cancellation (cooperative — the loop checks the token)
        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful shutdown, but don't wait forever
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO force-kill equivalent in .NET 8. You must
            // ensure all blocking calls accept CancellationToken.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No force-kill exists** | There's no `Thread.Abort()` replacement. If `GetNextItem()` blocks without accepting a `CancellationToken`, your `Stop` will hang. Every blocking call must be cancellation-aware. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** | `Thread.Sleep` blocks a thread-pool thread. Use `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` instead. |
| **`volatile bool` is unnecessary** | `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` is already thread-safe. Drop the `volatile` flag. |
| **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** | Always store the returned `Task` and await it during shutdown, or unobserved exceptions will be silently swallowed (or crash the process depending on config). |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`** | Always dispose it. The class itself should implement `IDisposable`. |
| **Legacy sync APIs** | If `GetNextItem()` can't be made async, wrap it but still check the token: `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between steps. |

## If You Can't Make Blocking Calls Async

For legacy code where a synchronous call truly can't accept a token:

```csharp
// Fallback: run on a dedicated thread so you don't starve the pool,
// and use a completion source to bridge to Task-based shutdown.
_workerTask = Task.Factory.StartNew(
    () => ProcessLoopSync(_cts.Token),
    _cts.Token,
    TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning,  // gets its own thread
    TaskScheduler.Default);
```

This mirrors the old `Thread.IsBackground = true` pattern but integrates with `Task`-based cancellation.

## Summary

`Thread.Abort()` relied on **preemptive** cancellation (the runtime yanked the thread). .NET 8 only supports **cooperative** cancellation — your code must check `CancellationToken` and exit voluntarily. The migration is not mechanical; you must audit every blocking call to ensure it accepts a token.
